## Type Coercion

### Example 5: Automatic Type Detection

```javascript
const csv = `id,name,active,score,percentage,created_at
1,Project A,true,95.5,87.3,2024-01-01
2,Project B,false,82.0,null,2024-01-02
3,Project C,TRUE,null,92.1,2024-01-03`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

result.rows.forEach(row => {
  console.log(`
    ID: ${row.id} (${typeof row.id})
    Name: ${row.name} (${typeof row.name})
    Active: ${row.active} (${typeof row.active})
    Score: ${row.score} (${typeof row.score})
    Percentage: ${row.percentage}
  `);
});

// Output:
// ID: 1 (number)
// Name: Project A (string)
// Active: true (boolean)
// Score: 95.5 (number)
// Percentage: 87.3 (number)
//
// ID: 2 (number)
// Name: Project B (string)
// Active: false (boolean)
// Score: 82 (number)
// Percentage: null (object)
//
// ID: 3 (number)
// Name: Project C (string)
// Active: true (boolean)
// Score: null (object)
// Percentage: 92.1 (number)
```

### Example 6: Type-Safe Operations

```javascript
const csv = `item,quantity,price
apple,10,1.50
banana,15,0.75
orange,8,2.00`;

const result = parseCSV(csv);

// Safe arithmetic with coerced numbers
result.rows.forEach(row => {
  const total = row.quantity * row.price;
  console.log(`${row.item}: ${row.quantity} × $${row.price} = $${total.toFixed(2)}`);
});

// Output:
// apple: 10 × $1.5 = $15.00
// banana: 15 × $0.75 = $11.25
// orange: 8 × $2 = $16.00
```

