# Manual Testing Guide for CSV Parser

This guide provides manual test cases that can be run to verify the CSV parser functionality. Each test includes the input, expected output, and how to verify it.

## Test Environment Setup

```javascript
// Load the CSV parser
const { parseCSV } = require('./csv-parser.js');

// Or in TypeScript:
// import { parseCSV } from './csv-parser';

// Copy-paste the test code into Node.js REPL or your IDE
```

---

## Category 1: Basic Parsing Tests

### Test 1.1: Simple CSV with Headers and Data
```javascript
const csv = 'name,age,city\nJohn,30,NYC\nJane,25,LA';
const result = parseCSV(csv);

// Verify:
console.assert(result.headers.length === 3, 'Should have 3 headers');
console.assert(result.headers[0] === 'name', 'First header is name');
console.assert(result.rows.length === 2, 'Should have 2 rows');
console.assert(result.rows[0].name === 'John', 'First row name is John');
console.assert(result.rows[0].age === 30, 'Age is number 30');
console.assert(result.rows[1].city === 'LA', 'Second row city is LA');
console.assert(result.errors.length === 0, 'No errors');
console.log('✓ Test 1.1 passed');
```

### Test 1.2: Single Column CSV
```javascript
const csv = 'name\nAlice\nBob\nCharlie';
const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.assert(result.headers.length === 1, 'Should have 1 header');
console.assert(result.rows.length === 3, 'Should have 3 rows');
console.assert(result.rows[0].name === 'Alice', 'First row is Alice');
console.assert(result.rows[2].name === 'Charlie', 'Third row is Charlie');
console.log('✓ Test 1.2 passed');
```

### Test 1.3: Single Row CSV
```javascript
const csv = 'a,b,c\n1,2,3';
const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.assert(result.rows.length === 1, 'Should have 1 row');
console.assert(result.rows[0].a === 1, 'Value coerced to number');
console.assert(result.rows[0].b === 2, 'Second value is number');
console.assert(result.rows[0].c === 3, 'Third value is number');
console.log('✓ Test 1.3 passed');
```

---

## Category 2: Quoted Fields Tests

### Test 2.1: Field with Comma Inside Quotes
```javascript
const csv = 'name,description\nJohn,"A person, born in 1990"';
const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.assert(result.rows.length === 1, 'Should parse 1 row');
console.assert(
  result.rows[0].description === 'A person, born in 1990',
  'Should preserve comma inside quotes'
);
console.log('✓ Test 2.1 passed');
```

### Test 2.2: Multiple Commas Inside Quotes
```javascript
const csv = 'text\n"a,b,c,d,e"';
const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.assert(result.rows[0].text === 'a,b,c,d,e', 'Should preserve all commas');
console.log('✓ Test 2.2 passed');
```

### Test 2.3: Quoted Field at Start and End
```javascript
const csv = 'data\n"hello"\n"world"';
const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.assert(result.rows[0].data === 'hello', 'Should remove surrounding quotes');
console.assert(result.rows[1].data === 'world', 'Second quoted field works');
console.log('✓ Test 2.3 passed');
```

---

## Category 3: Escaped Quotes Tests

### Test 3.1: Double Quotes = Single Quote
```javascript
const csv = 'message\n"She said ""hello"""';
const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.assert(result.rows[0].message === 'She said "hello"', 'Should unescape quotes');
console.log('✓ Test 3.1 passed');
```

### Test 3.2: Multiple Escaped Quotes
```javascript
const csv = 'text\n"Quote: ""Hi, how are you?"""';
const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.assert(
  result.rows[0].text === 'Quote: "Hi, how are you?"',
  'Should handle escaped quotes with punctuation'
);
console.log('✓ Test 3.2 passed');
```

### Test 3.3: Only Escaped Quotes
```javascript
const csv = 'x\n""""\n"""""""';
const result = parseCSV(csv);

console.assert(result.rows[0].x === '"', 'Four quotes become one');
console.assert(result.rows[1].x === '"""', 'Seven quotes become three');
console.log('✓ Test 3.3 passed');
```

